                <span id="dsq-author-user-65422">zer0_0zor0</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-65422" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-65422" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Your mentioning &#8220;blue jeans&#8221; makes for a good example to illustrate the point.</p>
<p>Blue jeans are a blue collar work garment not associated with the cultural milieu in which kimono have developed. The world of kimono is sophisticated, and historically varied. During the Edo period, for example, there was a trend to develop louder and more flamboyant patterns than those associated with the more conservative court life in Kyoto.</p>
<p>At any rate, the thing to compare blue jeans with in Japanese garment would be the jimbe and, to a lesser degree, the samue (temple work garment).</p>
</div>
        </div>

