        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-67016" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-67016" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>This doesn&#8217;t sound right. Next time when a Japanese asks me if they can wear my country&#8217;s clothes I am going to feed them the same BS instead of accepting them culturally.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-67214">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-67214" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-67214">
                <a id="dsq-author-user-67214" href="http://www.turning-japanese.info/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Eido INOUE</a>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-67214" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-67214" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Their incompetency is stunning in this regard. Museums have had to deal with protesters who have demanded censorship and changes to exhibits since as long as I can remember.</p>
<p>And these old-school outraged-at-the-museum-folk didn&#8217;t just try to censor, they tried to damage works of art too.</p>
<p>Back in my day, the pro-censorship people tended to be religious and they protested things like nudity or using one of their religious systems or figures for art in a way they did not approve of.</p>
<p>I guess in the 21st century, these puritan zealots and religious fundamentalists have been replaced by social justice warriors.</p>
<p>Anyway, my point is: the museum should have already had policies to deal with this sort of protest, as protesting museums and its exhibits is nothing new.</p>
<p>The MFA staff is in need of remedial training imo.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
